  

<p><img src="https://cdn.blot.im/blog_177bc256f0ee469c998e912e20ece048/_image_cache/5caf2698-9bee-45e5-bf36-c7deb7df76e4.png" alt="wooden fences in a suburban setting with bushes" width="1328" height="956"> <em>Photo of fences in Victoria, Australia, by the Author</em></p>
<p>There is peace in boundaries<br>
In knowing that beyond certain fences<br>
Lie lands that make wild promises<br>
But sow seeds of devastation</p>
<p>There is wisdom in boundaries<br>
In knowing that some restrictions heal<br>
While others oppress, and that<br>
I can know the difference between them</p>
<p>There is joy in boundaries<br>
In knowing that while I long to be free<br>
True freedom requires restraint<br>
And so, smiling, I dance toward the light</p>
<hr>
<p>Everything we say <em>yes</em> to implies a <em>no</em> to something else (or at least a <em>not yet</em>). The latter are the boundaries that protect our time as well as our physical, emotional, and mental wellbeing.</p>
